    <p>How do you pre­vent pests from eat­ing the flower buds of or­chid spikes?</p>
    <p>Ong Eng Siong</p>
    <p>Com­mon pests that con­sume or­chid flower buds and petals in­clude bee­tles and slugs. These are large pests that can be eas­ily ex­cluded if de­vel­op­ing in­flo­res­cences are pro­tected with a phys­i­cal bar­rier.</p>
    <p>In nurs­eries, it is com­mon to see plants be­ing cul­ti­vated in net­ted en­clo­sures, which are a sus­tain­able and chem­i­cal-free method to re­duce dam­age caused by these gar­den pests.</p>
    <p>stlife@sph.com.sg •</p>
    <p>An­swers by Dr Wil­son Wong, an NParks-cer­ti­fied prac­tis­ing hor­ti­cul­tur­ist, parks man­ager and ISA-cer­ti­fied ar­borist. He is the founder of Green Cul­ture Sin­ga­pore and an ad­junct as­sis­tant pro­fes­sor (Food Science & Tech­nol­ogy) at the Na­tional Univer­sity of Sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>Have a gar­den­ing query? E-mail it with clear, high-res­o­lu­tion pic­tures of at least 1MB, if any, and your full name to stlife@sph.com.sg. We re­serve the right to edit and re­ject ques­tions.</p>


